00:09:34.990 --> 00:09:38.185
OK, this is an observer who must
be accelerated, in some sense.

00:09:38.185 --> 00:09:41.140
And there must be some
kind of a mechanism that

00:09:41.140 --> 00:09:44.410
is allowing this observer to
hover at the fixed location

00:09:44.410 --> 00:09:47.140
in spacetime where they are at.

00:09:47.140 --> 00:09:50.380
So when I put these two
constraints together

00:09:50.380 --> 00:09:55.670
and I tie it into
that spacetime,

00:09:55.670 --> 00:10:02.420
what I find is that the timelike
component is 1 square root

00:10:02.420 --> 00:10:04.550
of 1 minus 2GM over r.

00:10:09.730 --> 00:10:17.680
So let's compare the energy
that is emitted at radius

00:10:17.680 --> 00:10:26.163
r to the energy that is absorbed
at some radius big R. So

00:10:26.163 --> 00:10:27.080
I'm going to imagine--

00:10:42.146 --> 00:10:44.260
And so the reason I formulate
it in this way, what

00:10:44.260 --> 00:10:47.560
I want to do now is
ask myself, well,

00:10:47.560 --> 00:10:52.690
what is the energy that
an observer at little r

00:10:52.690 --> 00:10:53.500
would measure here?

00:11:10.200 --> 00:11:12.190
What is the energy
that is observed

00:11:12.190 --> 00:11:18.650
by the person at
radius capital R?

00:11:18.650 --> 00:11:21.500
And now, we know, if I
imagine that these are both

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:37.710
being measured by
static observers,

00:11:37.710 --> 00:11:41.010
because P sub T, P
sub 0 or P sub T,

00:11:41.010 --> 00:11:59.320
because it is a constant as
the light propagates out,

00:11:59.320 --> 00:12:02.600
I can take the
ratio of these two.

00:12:02.600 --> 00:12:11.240
And the energy observed at
capital R versus the energy

00:12:11.240 --> 00:12:12.350
emitted at little r--

00:12:17.292 --> 00:12:18.000
Hang on a second.

00:12:27.950 --> 00:12:29.570
As I was looking
